Strings and Text-as-Data Walkthrough

String Manipulations

Example 1

We’ll use what we know of manipulation to clean the following string.

dirty_string = "22Clean 5674.5this $%&*_@string!"
dirty_string
## [1] "22Clean 5674.5this $%&*_@string!"

Remove the numbers…

dirty_string = str_remove_all(dirty_string,"\\d")
dirty_string
## [1] "Clean .this $%&*_@string!"

Remove the odd punctuation.

dirty_string = str_remove_all(dirty_string,"[:punct:]")
dirty_string
## [1] "Clean this $string"
dirty_string = str_remove_all(dirty_string,"\\$")
dirty_string
## [1] "Clean this string"

Example 2

dirty_text <-"

    A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.

They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy - who played the president on TV - received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.

The two - who have expressed largely pro-EU opinions - are set to take part in a run-off election next month.


"

dirty_text
## [1] "\n\n    A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.\n\nThey say Volodymyr Zelenskiy - who played the president on TV - received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.\n\nThe two - who have expressed largely pro-EU opinions - are set to take part in a run-off election next month.\n\n\n"

Remove the excess white space

dirty_text <- str_trim(dirty_text)
dirty_text
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.\n\nThey say Volodymyr Zelenskiy - who played the president on TV - received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.\n\nThe two - who have expressed largely pro-EU opinions - are set to take part in a run-off election next month."

Remove the spacing in the middle of the text (\n = “return”/“new line”)

dirty_text <- str_remove_all(dirty_text,"\\n")
dirty_text
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy - who played the president on TV - received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.The two - who have expressed largely pro-EU opinions - are set to take part in a run-off election next month."

Let’s remove the subordinate clauses.

text_list <- str_split(dirty_text," - ")
text_list
## [[1]]
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy"
## [2] "who played the president on TV"                                                                                                                                             
## [3] "received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.The two"                                                                                   
## [4] "who have expressed largely pro-EU opinions"                                                                                                                                 
## [5] "are set to take part in a run-off election next month."
text_list <- text_list[[1]]
text_list <- text_list[c(-2,-4)]
text_list
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy"
## [2] "received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.The two"                                                                                   
## [3] "are set to take part in a run-off election next month."
dirty_text <-  str_c(text_list,collapse = " ")
dirty_text
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls.They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%.The two are set to take part in a run-off election next month."

Add spaces between the sentences (but need to make sure we don’t split up the percentages!)

dirty_text <- str_replace_all(dirty_text,"\\.(?!\\d)",". ") 
dirty_text 
## [1] "A comedian with no political experience has won the most votes in the first round of Ukraine's presidential elections, according to exit polls. They say Volodymyr Zelenskiy received 30.4% of the vote, with current leader Petro Poroshenko second on 17.8%. The two are set to take part in a run-off election next month. "

Clean data.

dat <- 
  inaug_dat %>% 
  transmute(president = str_to_lower(Name) %>% str_replace_all(.," ","_"),
            address = ifelse(str_detect(`Inaugural Address`,"First"),"first","second"),
            date = as.Date(Date,"%A, %B %d, %Y"),
            year = lubridate::year(date),
            length = str_count(text),
            text = text)

# Adjust for one problematic date
dat[dat$president=="bill_clinton" & dat$address=="second",]$date = as.Date("1997-01-20")
dat[dat$president=="bill_clinton" & dat$address=="second",]$year = 1997

Convert text to tidy format.

text_dat <- 
  dat %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word,text)

Remove stopwords and digits.

text_dat <- 
  text_dat %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words,by="word") %>% 
  filter(!str_detect(word,"\\d")) %>% 
  
  # From the TM package (must install if you don't have)
  mutate(word = tm::removePunctuation(word))

Count term frequencies.

text_dat_freq <-
  text_dat %>% 
  group_by(president,address,year) %>% 
  count(word,sort=T) %>% 
  ungroup()

Top 25 most common words?

text_dat_freq %>% 
  mutate(word = reorder(word,n)) %>% 
  slice(1:25) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(word,n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()

Let’s look at the top ten words by president.

text_dat_freq %>% 
  group_by(president) %>% 
  top_n(10,n) %>%

  coord_flip() +

  theme(text = element_text(size=18))

Let’s examine the sentiment of the most recent Republican presidents.

text_dat_sent %>% 
  filter(president %in% c("george_w._bush","donald_j._trump")) %>% 
  group_by(president,address) %>% 
  mutate(index = row_number()) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  mutate(id = str_glue("{president} ({address})"),
         classify = ifelse(value>0,"steelblue","orangered")) %>% 
  
  # Now plot
  ggplot(aes(index,value,fill=classify)) +

  scale_fill_identity() +

  theme(text = element_text(size=16))

Let’s explore a different sentiment classifier and see if we get a similar story. Note that we’ll do everything all in one seamless pipeline. Recall that the bing sentiment classifier is binary (“positive”/“negative”)

# First Classify
text_dat %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("bing"),by='word') %>%
  
  
  # Next subset out the relevant presidents
  filter(president %in% c("george_w._bush","donald_j._trump")) %>% 
  group_by(president,address) %>% 
  mutate(index = row_number()) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  mutate(id = str_glue("{president} ({address})"),
         classify = ifelse(sentiment=="positive","steelblue","darkred")) %>% 
  
  # Now plot
  ggplot(aes(index,president,fill=classify)) +
  geom_tile(show.legend = F) +
  facet_wrap(~id,scales = "free",ncol=1) +
  scale_fill_identity() +
  labs(y="") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(text = element_text(size=16))

Looks largely the same…

Topic Models

Let’s run a topic model on the last 30 years of inaugural speeches and explore the types of topics they covered.

Let’s subset the text and convert to a document term matrix.

dtm <- 
  text_dat %>% 
  # filter(year >= 1989) %>% 
  mutate(id = str_glue("{president} ({address})")) %>% 
  group_by(id) %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  cast_dtm(document = id,term = word,value = n) 

dtm
## <<DocumentTermMatrix (documents: 56, terms: 8611)>>
## Non-/sparse entries: 32955/449261
## Sparsity           : 93%
## Maximal term length: 17
## Weighting          : term frequency (tf)

Let’s run a topic model with 4 possible topics.

inaug_lda <- LDA(dtm,k=2,control = list(seed = 1234))

Let’s explore the topic output.

What are the top ten words most associated with each topic?

# Extract the term to topic associations
inaug_lda %>% 
  tidy(metric="beta") %>% 
  
  # Convert topics metrics to proportions
  group_by(topic) %>% 
  mutate(prop = beta/sum(beta)) %>% 
  
  # Grab the top 10
  top_n(10,prop) %>% 
  ungroup %>% 
  
  # Rename topic label
  mutate(topic_label = str_glue("Topic {topic}")) %>% 
  
  # Plot as word cloud
  ggplot(aes(label=term,size=prop)) +
  ggwordcloud::geom_text_wordcloud_area() + 
  scale_size_area(max_size = 15) +
  facet_wrap(~topic_label,scales="free",ncol=2)

Can we associate meaning to these topics?

Let’s associate presidents speeches to specific topic entries. We can easily re-associate our topic allocations with the words used to find which presidents were most associated with the two topics.

pres_topic_member <- tidy(inaug_lda,"gamma") %>% 
  mutate(gamma = round(gamma,3))
pres_topic_member

Merge the two data sources and examine the change in topic membership over time…

full_join(pres_topic_member,year_key,by = "document") %>% 
  mutate(topic = ifelse(topic==1,"Internal Focus","External Focus")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year,gamma,fill=topic)) +
  geom_col(position="stack") +
  ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind() +
  ggthemes::theme_tufte() +
  labs(y="Proportion",x="Years") +
  theme(text=element_text(size=20))
